    differentiationNotes: `Struggling learners benefit from explaining how a wind-up toy works by storing energy in a spring when wound up and releasing that energy as motion when let go, converting potential energy to kinetic energy like a stretched rubber band snapping back \u2014 and calculating the cost of manufacturing toys using multiplication, such as if each toy costs three dollars to make and the factory produces eighty toys, the total manufacturing cost is two hundred forty dollars. Advanced learners benefit from analyzing how multiple physics principles work together in a single toy, explaining that a yo-yo simultaneously demonstrates gravity pulling it downward, potential energy converting to kinetic energy as it falls, angular momentum keeping it spinning at the bottom, string tension transmitting force between the string and the axle, and kinetic energy converting back to potential energy as the spin winds the string and lifts the yo-yo \u2014 and writing a multi-paragraph report about how the Industrial Revolution transformed toy making from expensive handcrafted items available only to wealthy families to affordable mass-produced toys accessible to all children, with specific examples like tin toys, rubber balls, and eventually plastic toys that could be molded into any shape at low cost.`,
    parentTakeaway: `Toys as physics \u2014 observe physics in action through play: notice how spinning tops stay upright through angular momentum and wobble (precess) in larger circles as they slow down because angular momentum decreases; observe how wind-up toys store energy in springs that is released as motion, converting potential energy to kinetic energy; compare how different balls bounce by dropping them from the same height and measuring bounce heights, discovering that a superball returns most of its energy as bounce while a tennis ball returns less (this difference is the coefficient of restitution); watch a yo-yo convert between potential and kinetic energy as it falls and rises; discuss how toys are designed considering safety (no small parts for young children), durability (stronger materials cost more), cost (more features mean higher prices), and fun (the most important factor); calculate toy prices and manufacturing costs using multiplication; discuss how toys have changed throughout history from ancient handmade wooden and clay toys to mass-produced tin and plastic toys to modern electronic games.`,
